AGI - Ebrahim Raisi>, whose fate remains uncertain after the news of the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-19/ helicopter-president-iraniano-raisi-26446918/"> helicopter crash on which he traveled in the Northwest of the country, has been president of the Islamic Republic for three years, contests Aytollah Raisi, 63 years old, is considered an ultraconservative and was the candidate supported by the Supreme Guide, Ali Khamenei, in the presidential elections of 2021, when the main rivals were prevented from applying. With the presidency of Raisi, all branches of power in Iran have ended up under the control of the anti-Western extremist factions, faithful to Khamenei, and the repression of dissent has intensified.
&nbsp;
Presenting himself as a champion of disadvantaged classes and the fight against corruption, Raisi was elected on 18 June 2021 in the first round of a vote characterized by a record abstention and the absence of real competitors. It happened to the most moderate Hassan Rouhani >- author of the 2015 nuclear agreement - which had beaten him in the 2017 presidential elections but which could no longer fall after two consecutive mandates. Raisi was strengthened by the legislative elections held last March, the first national consultation after the vast protest movement Woman, life, freedom that shook Iran at the end of 2022, following the death of Mahsa Amini>, the dead girl in Tehran while she was in custody of the moral police, who had arrested her because she would not wear the veil properly. Parliament, which will be chaired on 27 May, will be largely under the control of conservatives and ultra-conservatives, who support its government.
&nbsp;
In recent months, Raisi presented himself as a resolute opponent of Israel, the sworn enemy of the Islamic Republic, supporting Hamas from the beginning of the war with Israel in the Gaza Strip, followed by the slaughter of October 7 in the kibbutz. He welcomed Iran's unprecedented attack on 13 April against Israel, with 350 drones and missiles, most of which were intercepted with the help of the United States and many other allied countries. Born in November 1960 in the Shiite Holy City of Mashhad (North-East), Raisi made a career in the judicial system for three decades, after being appointed Attorney General of Karaj, near Tehran, only 20 years old, in the wake of the victory of the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
&nbsp;
In 2016, Khamenei led him to the powerful charity Astan Quds Razavi, which manages the mausoleum of Imam Reza in Mashhad as well as an immense industrial and real estate heritage. In 2019, Khamenei puts him in the lead of the judiciary and shortly after they took the US sanctions against him, for the role he played in the executions of thousands of political prisoners in 1988; a responsibility that earned him the nickname of "the slaughterhouse of Tehran". Iran has never recognized such killings. As feared by the dissidents, his presidency has seen a surge in capital and repression executions.
&nbsp;
Without much charisma and always with in the head the classic black turban that characterizes the 'seyyed', the descendants of Muhammad, Raisi attended the courses of religion and Islamic jurisprudence of the ayatollah Khamenei. He is married to Jamileh Alamolhoda, professor of education science at Shahid Beheshti University of Tehran, from whom he had two daughters. The Iranian president is considered among the favourites for succession to the elderly and sick Khamenei. If he had lost his life in today's incident, the government's leadership would pass to his deputy, Mohammad Mokhber>, and new elections should be undecided within the next 50 days.

