AGI - The Egyptian Court of Cassation announced on Saturday the decision to remove the name of the Egyptian football legend Mohamed Aboutrika, as well as of another 1,500 people for their alleged ties with the Muslim Brotherhood, from the list of the country of "terrorism". In a statement, the court observed that in addition to being removed from this black list, also its ban on expatriation and the seizure of its funds were revoked.
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The Court of Cassation has heard our arguments and has decided to cancel the judgment of the Criminal Court and to postpone the case for the examination to another court," said Egyptian lawyer Khaled Ali on his official account X. The Cairo Criminal Tribunal designated Aboutrika in 2017 as a "terrorist" for allegedly funding the Muslim Brotherhood, an outlaw group in Egypt and considered a terrorist since 2013. A year later, the Office of the Attorney General requested that his name be included in the list of "terrorism" of the country for five years, and last year the Office of the Attorney General decided to renew it for another five years.
<div </div
&nbsp;
This extension is the one which was rejected by the Court of Cassation, so that this case becomes the responsibility of another court. The former Egyptian footballer publicly supported Mohamed Morsi for the presidency of Egypt, which won in 2012 in the country's first democratic elections, although a year after the former leader of the Muslim Brotherhood was overthrown by current President Abdefaltah al-Sisi, in a military coup.
With 102 appearances and twice African champion (2006 and 2008), this Qatari offensive midfielder who works as a commentator for the Bein Sports channel, was compared to French Zinedine Zidane for his style of play and was voted best African player in club competitions in 2008.
